  "answer": "Both The Seafarer and Cynewulf's runic epilogues pivot to prayer at their close, but they are doing different theological work, and Cynewulf's epilogues are significantly richer.\n\nThe Seafarer (unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e, ch. 5) closes in paragraphs p-4ea5bb and p-1c332d. After its meditation on earthly vanity and the terror of 'the Measurer,' it turns communal and hortatory: 'Let us think where we have our home… let us strive that we may be allowed into that eternal blessedness.' It ends in a brief doxology: 'Thanks be to the Holy One, the Prince of Glory, the everlasting Lord, that He has honored us for all time. Amen.' The prayer is gratitude-forward, collective in voice ('us'), and theologically clean — it gestures at eschatology but does not elaborate it. There is no personal confession of sin, no petition for intercession, and no sustained vision of judgment.\n\nCynewulf's runic epilogues — in Elene (cynewulf-elene-d2d132, ch. 1, paragraphs p-d2e607, p-8f8a1b, p-dcbbfe) and Juliana (cynewulf-juliana-9a2157, ch. 1, paragraphs p-e769dc, p-1f8ce8) — each perform multiple theological moves the Seafarer does not.\n\nIn Elene: Cynewulf opens the epilogue in first-person confession — 'I was stained by my deeds, shackled by sins, worn down by sorrows, bitterly bound, beset by troubles' — before narrating his reception of divine grace through the gift of poetry ('until the mighty King granted me learning through a luminous form'). He then delivers a full eschatological vision of the Last Judgment: three groups sorted into fire, the sinful refined like gold in a furnace, the damned cast into hell's abyss. The closing is implicitly intercessory — the entire vision motivates the reader to seek the better path — and ends with 'Amen.'\n\nIn Juliana: Cynewulf is more explicit. He directly petitions the saint herself for intercession at the moment of death ('I have great need that the holy one should grant me her help, when my dearest companions, my soul and my body, are divided'). The runic letters encode his name within expressions of spiritual dread (Torch, Bow, Need, Journey, Joy, Strength, Sea — the runic names spelling CYNEWULF). He then closes with an explicit Trinitarian address: 'Grant us, God of might, that we may find Your face… the Father, the Spirit of comfort… and the dear Son… mild and merciful in that glorious time. Amen.'\n\nContrast: The Seafarer's close is a clean doxological turn — grateful, communal, aspirational — but it lacks the personal confessional register, the mediatorial (saintly intercession) dimension, and the elaborate eschatological scaffolding that Cynewulf builds in Elene and Juliana. Cynewulf's prayers are richer: they move from self-accusation through petition for grace, through Last Judgment vision or saintly intercession, to Trinitarian address. The Seafarer ends in gratitude; Cynewulf ends in mercy-seeking. One is a thanksgiving, the other a plea — and theologically, the plea is the more fully worked-out devotional act. Andreas (cynewulf-andreas-07b573) lacks a comparable runic epilogue and ends instead with the people's praise, so does not factor into this comparison.",
